{"content":[{"id":"3fe8dae6","settings":{"flex_direction":"column","content_width":"full","padding":{"unit":"px","top":"0","right":"20","bottom":"0","left":"20","isLinked":false}},"elements":[{"id":"77761091","settings":{"title":"Understanding Frozen Shoulder and Its Effective Treatments\n","__globals__":{"title_color":"globals\/colors?id=primary"}},"elements":[],"isInner":false,"widgetType":"heading","elType":"widget"},{"id":"15c5d5fa","settings":{"editor":"Frozen shoulder, also known as adhesive capsulitis, is a condition that causes pain and stiffness in the shoulder joint. It often develops gradually and can significantly affect mobility and quality of life. This blog discusses what causes frozen shoulder and how modern orthopedic care can help relieve symptoms and restore motion.\n\n","typography_typography":"custom","typography_font_size":{"unit":"px","size":18,"sizes":[]},"typography_line_height":{"unit":"px","size":28,"sizes":[]}},"elements":[],"isInner":false,"widgetType":"text-editor","elType":"widget"},{"id":"5b9b03d5","settings":{"title":"What is Frozen Shoulder?\n","header_size":"h4","__globals__":{"title_color":"globals\/colors?id=primary"}},"elements":[],"isInner":false,"widgetType":"heading","elType":"widget"},{"id":"1d5cf94e","settings":{"editor":"Frozen shoulder, also known as adhesive capsulitis, is a condition characterized by stiffness, pain, and limited range of motion in the shoulder joint. It develops gradually and can severely restrict daily activities. The condition typically progresses through stages and may take months to years to fully resolve, with or without treatment.\n\n","typography_typography":"custom","typography_font_size":{"unit":"px","size":18,"sizes":[]},"typography_line_height":{"unit":"px","size":28,"sizes":[]}},"elements":[],"isInner":false,"widgetType":"text-editor","elType":"widget"},{"id":"445a5d0e","settings":{"title":"Symptoms and Diagnosis\n","header_size":"h4","__globals__":{"title_color":"globals\/colors?id=primary"}},"elements":[],"isInner":false,"widgetType":"heading","elType":"widget"},{"id":"58c22676","settings":{"title":"1. Gradual Onset of Shoulder Pain\n","header_size":"h3","__globals__":{"title_color":"globals\/colors?id=text"}},"elements":[],"isInner":false,"widgetType":"heading","elType":"widget"},{"id":"5c64e5b2","settings":{"editor":"Frozen shoulder often begins with mild pain that worsens over time, especially at night or during arm movement.\n\n","typography_typography":"custom","typography_font_size":{"unit":"px","size":18,"sizes":[]},"typography_line_height":{"unit":"px","size":28,"sizes":[]}},"elements":[],"isInner":false,"widgetType":"text-editor","elType":"widget"},{"id":"324af3a","settings":{"title":"2. Stiffness and Limited Range of Motion\n","header_size":"h3","__globals__":{"title_color":"globals\/colors?id=text"}},"elements":[],"isInner":false,"widgetType":"heading","elType":"widget"},{"id":"1ffe0891","settings":{"editor":"As the condition progresses, the shoulder becomes increasingly stiff, making it difficult to lift the arm or perform routine tasks like reaching or dressing.\n\n","typography_typography":"custom","typography_font_size":{"unit":"px","size":18,"sizes":[]},"typography_line_height":{"unit":"px","size":28,"sizes":[]}},"elements":[],"isInner":false,"widgetType":"text-editor","elType":"widget"},{"id":"18bd4a72","settings":{"title":"3. Three Distinct Phases\n","header_size":"h3","__globals__":{"title_color":"globals\/colors?id=text"}},"elements":[],"isInner":false,"widgetType":"heading","elType":"widget"},{"id":"2036ee2b","settings":{"editor":"The condition typically advances in three stages: the \"freezing\" phase (increasing pain and stiffness), the \"frozen\" phase (reduced pain but severe stiffness), and the \"thawing\" phase (gradual improvement in motion).\n\n","typography_typography":"custom","typography_font_size":{"unit":"px","size":18,"sizes":[]},"typography_line_height":{"unit":"px","size":28,"sizes":[]}},"elements":[],"isInner":false,"widgetType":"text-editor","elType":"widget"},{"id":"70145de1","settings":{"title":"4. Physical and Imaging Evaluation\n","header_size":"h3","__globals__":{"title_color":"globals\/colors?id=text"}},"elements":[],"isInner":false,"widgetType":"heading","elType":"widget"},{"id":"8c17dbe","settings":{"editor":"Diagnosis is usually based on clinical examination, history of limited movement, and may be supported by imaging like MRI or ultrasound to rule out other shoulder issues.\n\n","typography_typography":"custom","typography_font_size":{"unit":"px","size":18,"sizes":[]},"typography_line_height":{"unit":"px","size":28,"sizes":[]}},"elements":[],"isInner":false,"widgetType":"text-editor","elType":"widget"},{"id":"6ea1e6e0","settings":{"title":"Modern Treatment Options\n","header_size":"h4","__globals__":{"title_color":"globals\/colors?id=primary"}},"elements":[],"isInner":false,"widgetType":"heading","elType":"widget"},{"id":"d89530","settings":{"title":"1. Physical Therapy and Stretching\n","header_size":"h3","__globals__":{"title_color":"globals\/colors?id=text"}},"elements":[],"isInner":false,"widgetType":"heading","elType":"widget"},{"id":"5ead92ca","settings":{"editor":"Guided physical therapy is the cornerstone of treatment. Targeted stretching and mobility exercises help break adhesions and restore movement over time.\n\n","typography_typography":"custom","typography_font_size":{"unit":"px","size":18,"sizes":[]},"typography_line_height":{"unit":"px","size":28,"sizes":[]}},"elements":[],"isInner":false,"widgetType":"text-editor","elType":"widget"},{"id":"6ad14756","settings":{"title":"2. Medications for Pain Relief\n","header_size":"h3","__globals__":{"title_color":"globals\/colors?id=text"}},"elements":[],"isInner":false,"widgetType":"heading","elType":"widget"},{"id":"64b4ae06","settings":{"editor":"Over-the-counter pain relievers and anti-inflammatory medications (NSAIDs) can reduce discomfort and allow better participation in therapy sessions.\n\n","typography_typography":"custom","typography_font_size":{"unit":"px","size":18,"sizes":[]},"typography_line_height":{"unit":"px","size":28,"sizes":[]}},"elements":[],"isInner":false,"widgetType":"text-editor","elType":"widget"},{"id":"2b176628","settings":{"title":"3. Corticosteroid Injections\n","header_size":"h3","__globals__":{"title_color":"globals\/colors?id=text"}},"elements":[],"isInner":false,"widgetType":"heading","elType":"widget"},{"id":"2f028191","settings":{"editor":"Injections directly into the shoulder joint can reduce inflammation and pain, especially in the early stages of the condition.\n\n","typography_typography":"custom","typography_font_size":{"unit":"px","size":18,"sizes":[]},"typography_line_height":{"unit":"px","size":28,"sizes":[]}},"elements":[],"isInner":false,"widgetType":"text-editor","elType":"widget"},{"id":"655067ff","settings":{"title":"4. Hydrodilatation\n","header_size":"h3","__globals__":{"title_color":"globals\/colors?id=text"}},"elements":[],"isInner":false,"widgetType":"heading","elType":"widget"},{"id":"53028309","settings":{"editor":"This minimally invasive procedure involves injecting fluid into the joint capsule to stretch and release tight tissues, often done under imaging guidance.\n\n","typography_typography":"custom","typography_font_size":{"unit":"px","size":18,"sizes":[]},"typography_line_height":{"unit":"px","size":28,"sizes":[]}},"elements":[],"isInner":false,"widgetType":"text-editor","elType":"widget"},{"id":"5f9e2c10","settings":{"title":"5. Surgical Intervention\n","header_size":"h3","__globals__":{"title_color":"globals\/colors?id=text"}},"elements":[],"isInner":false,"widgetType":"heading","elType":"widget"},{"id":"3fc7bb15","settings":{"editor":"In severe or persistent cases, arthroscopic surgery may be recommended to release the tight joint capsule. This is usually followed by an aggressive rehabilitation program.\n\n","typography_typography":"custom","typography_font_size":{"unit":"px","size":18,"sizes":[]},"typography_line_height":{"unit":"px","size":28,"sizes":[]}},"elements":[],"isInner":false,"widgetType":"text-editor","elType":"widget"},{"id":"233eadb1","settings":{"title":"Who is at Risk?\n","header_size":"h4","__globals__":{"title_color":"globals\/colors?id=primary"}},"elements":[],"isInner":false,"widgetType":"heading","elType":"widget"},{"id":"50ca1430","settings":{"editor":"Frozen shoulder is more common in individuals aged 40 to 60, and it affects women more often than men. It is frequently associated with diabetes, thyroid disorders, shoulder injuries, and periods of immobility such as after surgery or stroke.\n\n","typography_typography":"custom","typography_font_size":{"unit":"px","size":18,"sizes":[]},"typography_line_height":{"unit":"px","size":28,"sizes":[]}},"elements":[],"isInner":false,"widgetType":"text-editor","elType":"widget"},{"id":"5536d23b","settings":{"title":"Conclusion","header_size":"h4","__globals__":{"title_color":"globals\/colors?id=primary"}},"elements":[],"isInner":false,"widgetType":"heading","elType":"widget"},{"id":"5480b137","settings":{"editor":"<p>Frozen shoulder can be a frustrating and painful condition, but with early diagnosis and a structured treatment plan, most people recover full or near-full shoulder function. Physical therapy and pain management are key, with surgical options available for resistant cases.<\/p>\n<p>If you're experiencing persistent shoulder pain and stiffness, consult an orthopedic specialist to determine the best course of action tailored to your condition and health profile.<\/p>","typography_typography":"custom","typography_font_size":{"unit":"px","size":18,"sizes":[]},"typography_line_height":{"unit":"px","size":28,"sizes":[]}},"elements":[],"isInner":false,"widgetType":"text-editor","elType":"widget"}],"isInner":false,"elType":"container"}],"settings":{"template":"default"},"metadata":[]}